  "english_translation": {
    "entry_translation": "Sūrat al-Nisāʾ.\n\nMedinan. It has no counterpart (naẓīrah) in its verse-count. Its words are three thousand nine hundred and forty-five, and its letters are sixteen thousand and thirty. It is one hundred and seventy-five verses in the two Madani counts, the Makki, and the Basri; one hundred and seventy-six in the Kufi; and one hundred and seventy-seven in the Shami.\n\nIts points of disagreement are two verse-endings: “an taḍillū al-sabīl” is counted by the Kufi and the Shami, and the rest do not count it; “fa-yuʿadhdhibahum ʿadhāban alīman” is counted by the Shami, and the rest do not count it.\n\nAbū al-Fatḥ, our shaykh, related to us; he said: Aḥmad b. Muḥammad related to us; he said: Aḥmad b. Shabīb related to us; he said: al-Faḍl related to us; he said: Khallād related to us, from ʿĪsā, from Ḥamza, from al-Aʿmash, from Ibrāhīm, from ʿAlqama, that he counted in Sūrat al-Nisāʾ “an taḍillū al-sabīl” as the head of verse forty-four.\n\nIn it there are six places that resemble verse-endings without being counted, by consensus: “falā tabghū ʿalayhinna sabīlan”; “lawlā akhkhartanā ilā ajalin qarīb”; “li-l-nāsi rasūlan”; “wa-Allāhu yaktubu mā yubayyitūn”; “wa-ittabiʿ millata Ibrāhīma ḥanīfan”; and “wa-lā al-malāʾikatu al-muqarrabūn.”",
    "ruus_translation_note": "The running رؤوس الآي are represented here as an ordered Arabic sequence on the later Madani baseline. The printed witness preserves external display numerals rather than a clean 1–175 later-Madani sequence: it skips the disputed Kufi/Shami head after displayed 43, breaks 131 across the 147/148 page boundary, and ends with a terminal blank 176 line. The normalized list below preserves the actual ordered head sequence and logs those source phenomena explicitly."
  },
